gh popular fiction, law codes, religious works, medical treatises, biographical material, and artistic treatments, Leupp traces the origins of pre-Tokugawa homosexual traditions among monks and samurai, then describes the emergence of homosexual practices among commoners in Tokugawa cities. He argues that it was "nurture" rather than "nature" that accounted for such conspicuous male/male sexuality and that bisexuality was more prevalent than homosexuality. Detailed, thorough, and very readable, this study is the first in English or Japanese to address so comprehensively one of the most complex and intriguing aspects of Japanese history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMale homosexualityzJapanxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aacademic.  aartistic treatments.  aasia.  aasian history.  abiographical material.  abisexuality.  aclass structure.  acommoners.  acultural history.  aearly modern jaan.  agay studies.  agay.  agender roles.  aglobal context.  ahistorical documentation.  ahomosexual traditions.  ajapanese history.  alaw codes.  algbt history.  aliterary documentation.  amale homosexual behavior.  amedical treatises.  amonks.  apolitics.  apopular fiction.  aqueer history.  areligious works.  asamurai.  asexual desire.  asexual expression.  asexual relations.  asexuality.  atokugawa bakufu.  atokugawa japan.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020900840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520919198?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919198423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919198/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  